CAP. X. Show mercy also, where mercy is fitting, and listen to the prayer of the poor and helpless. Let fit men of proper age and sufficient wisdom be appointed to administer justice.

CAP. XI. Be not exalted with vain glory, Ο king, or moved by sudden wrath to violence. Be liberal to those who need thy help, and give alms to the poor of that which God has given' thee. Avoid gluttony and sloth.

CAP. XIII. O king, thou art the defendet in arms of thy people. Remember the deeds of thy father, whose praise Is sounded everywhere and whose prowess was above that of Hector. He was just and liberal ; he made prey of foreign lands, but he protected his own. France and Spain both felt his might, and he broke through the ranke ot' his enemies like a lion. The land was at rest under that great prince: the nation was secure from its enemies. Ο king, endeavour to deserve the praise which thy father won. Peace is the best of all things, but it must sometimes give way to war.

CAP. XIV. A king must not prey upon his people; their love is his chief glory. He should remember that true nobility does not come from noble descent but from virtue. Study to know thysels and to love God.

CAP. XV. O young king, remember how Solomon in his youth asked for wisdom to rule well, rather than wealth or long life, and how God granted his prayer and added also the other blessings. Wisdom is above everything for a king, and this makes him acceptable to God.
